Fig. 4
 shows that the CERC of the GPUA increased from 1.73 in 2010 to 2.89 in 2021, representing a gradual increase of 67.05 %. Due to space limitations, the years 2010, 2014, 2017, and 2021 were selected as representative years to present the spatiotemporal evolution characteristics (Fig. 5
). In 2010, only Xi'an had a CERC greater than 0.20, while the remaining cities had a CERC lower than 0.16, which is relatively low. In 2014, Baoji and Xianyang had CERC in the range of 0.18â0.20, followed by Xi'an. Those of Shangluo and Linfen slightly decreased, while those of other cities improved. In 2017, Baoji was the second-largest city after Xi'an, with a CERC greater than 0.20, while the CERC of other cities also improved to between 0.16 and 0.20. In 2021, the number of cities with CERC greater than 0.20 increased to seven, which is more than half of the number of cities in the GPUA. However, the CERC of Pingliang was only 0.17, much smaller than that of Xi'an, which was 0.41 in 2010. The obvious differences in the CERC between the central city and neighbouring cities, and the lack of radiation drive by the central city to neighbouring cities cause the spatial distribution to be significantly imbalanced. This situation indicates that the improvement in collaborative governance capacity and the establishment of a carbon emission reduction synergistic mechanism are key for promoting the carbon governance of UAs.

The modified gravity model was used to establish the gravity matrix of the CERC. The spatial correlation network structure of the CERC in 2010, 2014, 2017, and 2021 was mapped by running the âNetdrawâ plug in a visualization tool in Ucinet software (Fig. 8
                           ). The results showed that the CERC of the GPUA had a significant spatial correlation and is becoming increasingly close. The spatial correlation network structure showed a complex pattern of multiple flows and threads. The characteristics of the central city were remarkable, indicating that the spatial correlation structure of CERC was not merely a simple geographical proximity relationship, but rather a typical core-edge pattern. The number of network relationships increased from 26 in 2010 to 71 in 2021 (Fig. 9
                           ), the network density increased from 0.24 to 0.65. The network hierarchies decreased from 0.91 in 2010 to 0.40 in 2021, reflecting the increasing relevance and stability of the network and the strengthening of CERC interactions between cities. The network correlations were continuously 1, indicating a significant spatial correlation between the cities. The network efficiencies were continuously 0, indicating that the network was not dependent on a single or few nodes. This situation resulted from the implementation of the Development Plan for the Guanzhong Plain urban agglomeration, which led to a steady increase in the carrying capacity of the urban ecosystem, the effectiveness of air pollution control in the Fenwei Plain, and a marked improvement in the quality of the ecological environment of the Qinling Mountains. Enhancement of the network correlation of the spatial structure of CERC in UAs has promoted synergistic development among cities, which has facilitated the realization of SDG13.2 âIntegrate climate change measures into policies and planningâ, SDG13.3 âBuild knowledge and capacity to meet climate changeâ, and SDG13.5 âPromote mechanisms to raise capacity for planning and managementâ.
